subanswer.text: Substituting $x=1$ into the equation $q(x)=bx+1$, we see that $q(1)=1+b$. The answer is $1+b$.

ost_step.1: Now substituting $q(1)=1+b$ into the equation $f(x)=x-3$, we get $f(q(1))=(1+b)-3=-2+b$.

direct_answer.text:
Let's think step by step. We know that $q(1) = b + 1.$ We also know that $f(q(1)) = -3,$ so we substitute both of these expressions into the function $f(x).$ Now substituting $q(1)=1+b$ into the equation $f(x)=x-3$, we get $f(q(1))=(1+b)-3=-2+b$. Setting this equal to $-3$ and solving for $b$ yields $$\begin{array}{lll} &&-2+b=-3\\
&\Rightarrow & \quad\,\ b=-3+2\\
&\Rightarrow & \quad\,\ b=-1 \end{array}\]Therefore, $b=-\boxed{1}$.
The answer is: -1.
